The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, February 10, 2004  Business Briefs																								 Mumbai, Feb. 9: The Securities and Exchange Board of India (Sebi) today asked mutual funds to use derivative products only for hedging and balancing of portfolio. The regulator said all derivative positions should be backed by cash or shares with the maximum investment pegged at 50 per cent of net assets. Sebi said, At no point in time the derivative position should result, even for few moments on an intra-day basis, in actual or potential leverage or short sale/short position on any underlying security.																								 Calcutta, Feb. 9: CESC Ltd has decided to amalgamate its wholly-owned subsidiaries, Balagarh Power Co Ltd and Cescon Ltd, with itself. It also plans to raise Rs 49.61 crore from the market by offering 82,69,788 equity shares of Rs 10 each at a premium of Rs 50 to its existing shareholders.																								 London, Feb. 9: Crude oil price was little changed as traders awaited a meeting tomorrow by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries on second-quarter production.																								 Mumbai, Feb. 9: Singapore Airlines is exploring investment opportunities in India. But actual investments would depend upon the regulatory environment, chairman Koh Bon Hwee said today.																								 Calcutta, Feb. 9: The Engineering Export Promotion Council has urged the US industry to lobby against the non-tariff barriers imposed by that country on Indian exports.
